tissue","Stimulates insulin-like growth factor 1 production","Inhibits lipolysis in adipose tissue","Reduces bone mineral density"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone\u0027s primary action is \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) production\u003C/strong\u003E by the liver. IGF-1 then mediates many of growth hormone\u0027s anabolic effects on tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone actually increases protein synthesis and promotes muscle growth rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreasing protein synthesis in muscle\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone has anti-insulin effects and reduces (rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Epromotes) glucose uptake into adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone increases bone mineral density and linear growth; therefore the statement that it \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduces\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone mineral density \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone promotes lipolysis and fat breakdown; it does not \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit lipolysis in adipose tissue. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone has important metabolic effects including increased protein synthesis, enhanced lipolysis, and reduced insulin sensitivity. These effects help mobilise energy substrates for growth and development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Growth hormone is released in a pulsatile fashion from the anterior pituitary gland under control of growth hormone releasing hormone.","Growth hormone stimulates production of insulin-like growth factor 1 from the liver, which mediates many of its growth-promoting effects.","Growth hormone has important metabolic effects including increased protein synthesis, lipolysis, and insulin resistance."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T15:53:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T13:04:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"created